## Phase 5 — Supabase client & sync queue
**Goal:** Cloud sync layer that drains the SQLite queue automatically when signal returns. Supabase is never written to directly — always via the queue.

```
Using CLAUDE.md and /src/types/schemas.ts, implement /src/services/supabase.ts and /src/services/syncQueue.ts:

supabase.ts:
1. Initialise Supabase client with project URL and anon key (use placeholder constants for now — we will swap in real keys)
2. Implement pushRecord(item: SyncQueueItem): Promise<boolean> — parses item.payload, inserts into the correct Supabase table based on item.table_name, returns true on success
3. All Supabase calls must be wrapped in try/catch — never throw, return false on failure

syncQueue.ts:
1. Use @react-native-community/netinfo to monitor connectivity
2. On connectivity change to online: call drainQueue()
3. drainQueue(): fetch all unsynced SyncQueueItems from SQLite, attempt pushRecord() for each, on success call markSynced(), on failure increment retry_count and save last_error, skip items with retry_count > 5
4. Implement exponential backoff: wait 2^retry_count seconds before retrying a failed item
5. Export startSyncMonitor() — call this once on app launch to begin watching connectivity
6. Export forcSync() — manually trigger drainQueue(), used for the demo sync button

Strict TypeScript. Never write to Supabase directly from any other file — only through syncQueue. Handle all network errors gracefully.
```

